rows.help: Total electric power consumption in November dropped slightly year over year, with a 11.2 kW decrease in peak demand. Pumps and fans accounted for approximately 11% of the total building electric usage this month, and cooling is supplied centrally by the campus. EcoVox is monitoring five air handlers in this building - AHUs 1 and 2, which serve the labs and run 24/7 to deliver a minimum of four air changes per hour; and AHUs 3, 4, and 5, which serve offices and classrooms. AHUs 3-5 each run slightly different hours, but generally about 6:30am to 9pm each day. AHU 3 generally runs at 60% fan speed, while AHU 5 and 4 run at 65% and 50% respectively. AHUs 1 and 2 have two fans each, but the AHU 1 supply air fan 1B shows no run time. There are also eight FCUs being monitored in this building, all of which run 24/7. The FCUs have cooling only except FCU 1, which also has heating available. Although cooling is available, it has rarely been enabled since EcoVox began monitoring, despite many FCU zone temperatures being above setpoint. Overall, the building has performed well this month. There are some data classes for which more frequent point sampling would be helpful, such as static pressure. This would give EcoVox more insight into how the building is operating. Many AHU 1 and 2 VAV zones also have static air flow points, which should be calibrated to ensure the zones meet the air flow requirements. For AHUs 3, 4, and 5, the cooling enables before the economizer reaches 100% if the outside air temperature is above the supply air temperature, even if outside air temperature continues to be below return air temperature. EcoVox estimates that there was an approximate potential savings of 300 ton-hours of refrigeration, or \$30, in November. We will keep an eye on this going forward to ensure it does not become a larger issue. Contact us at 805.540.2044 if we can be of assistance with any of the action items.

rows.help: Total electric power consumption at this site has decreased 16.6% compared to February 2015. The decrease is seen in the utility data as a 20-30 kW decrease throughout the day, including less intense afternoon demand spikes. In addition, the peak demand is 31 kW lower than in 2015, occurring this year on February 9 at 10:20am. Fans and pumps accounted for 15% of the total building power consumption in February, slightly higher than in recent months. Cooling is supplied centrally by the campus. All units except AHU 03 were offline February 21 through 23 and did not send data to EcoVox. FCUs 01, 07, and 08 used to run 24/7 like other FCUs, but throughout February they have been cycling off more frequently. These three FCUs also maintain very low zone temperatures. The other FCUs tend towards having zone temperatures above setpoint, and do not enable cooling when this occurs. AHU 1 runs approximately 66% fan speed 24/7, while AHU 2 runs approximately 57%. AHUs 3-5 fan speeds vary throughout the day, and these fans turn off overnight. The hot water system maintains the 160 degree supply water temperature setpoint 24/7, ensuring most zones meet heating setpoints well. VAV 3_12, however, appears to have a stuck heating valve - heating is enabled throughout the day, but supply air temperature remains low. Although occurring less frequently as the weather warms, there were still occasional periods in February during which all VAVs for a particular AHU were in reheat mode. Adjusting the control strategy for these units would result in energy savings by avoiding over-cooling of supply air. Contact us at 805.540.2044 if we can be of assistance with any of the action items.

rows.help: Total electric power consumption by Ghausi was 90,000 kWh this month, a decrease of 17% compared to July 2015. The peak demand has decreased by 21 kW to 215 kW. The pumps and fans monitored by EcoVox accounted for approximately 31% of the total building electric consumption, on par with last month. EcoVox will be reviewing the completed energy efficiency measures provided by the UC Davis team to analyze their current and future impact. All AHUs performed well this month, although AHU 3 supply air temperature tends to rise above setpoint during afternoons. The AHU 4 damper position trend is incorrect, and instead tracks outside air temperature. AHUs 3-5 appear to have a reset control strategy for duct static pressure, while the setpoints for AHUs 1-2 remain static at 1.5 inh2o. Overnight damper oscillation has been noted in many zones in this building. When zone temperature reaches the cooling setpoint the damper will open to allow airflow, then close once the zone is back within setpoint. Due to the small temperature buffer, oscillations end up occurring throughout the evening. This was discussed with the UC Davis team during the July 27 meeting, and will be followed up on to ensure optimal zone control during unoccupied periods. EcoVox can provide examples of specific instances or zones as needed. Issues with the VAV 5_05 zone temperature sensor persist. Although generally performing well, this sensor occasionally drops to 0 degrees for 24+ hours at a time. VAV 1_05 is generally the coolest zone, averaging under 66 degrees throughout the day. VAVs 1_01 and 1_02 also tend to be quite cool throughout occupied hours. VAV 3_19 is often the warmest zone during afternoons. Contact us at 805.540.2044 if we can be of assistance with any of the action items.

rows.help: Total electric power consumption during March was 286,000 kBTU, a 5% decrease compared to March 2016. Steam power consumption has decreased by 5% to 368,000 kBTU. Chilled water power consumption trends have remained static at 0 throughout the month, so EcoVox is unable to calculate year over year comparisons. Unoccupied baseline is level with last year, with most electric demand decreases occurring between 7am and 8pm. Units have generally performed well throughout the month. As noted below, the AHU 3-5 supply and return fan status have not been sending data, although static pressure and other trends confirm that these units continue to enable on their normal schedule. Note that the lack of run status has caused the "AHU Schedule Adj." and "Lab Min Supply Flow Adj. (Fan)" savings listed on page 1 to not calculate from March 2 onward, resulting in the listed savings being lower than actual. AHU 5 cycling during unoccupied periods has again been occurring, due to computer lab zones rising above setpoint and calling for cooling. Based on static pressure data, it appears that the enable frequently lasts for less than five minutes. Adjusting the minimum enable period on this unit could reduce cycling on the equipment while still meeting temperature setpoints. Contact us at 805.540.2044 if we can be of assistance with any of the action items.

rows.help: Total electric power consumption by Ghausi has decreased 18% compared to last year, and peak demand has similarly dropped. Fans and pumps accounted for 14% of the total building power consumption in March, slightly higher than in Feburary. Cooling is supplied centrally by the campus. EcoVox has been adding KPI trends for better understanding of how the building is operating, and for comparison across buildings. PES is also in the process of being set up, and analytics will begin soon. EcoVox noted a potential stuck heating valve on VAV 3_12 last month, in which heating was commanded at 100% but supply air temperature was not rising. On March 27 the control strategy of this zone changed, allowing the unit to run at less than 100% supply air flow. Since that adjustment zone temperature has been moderated by air flow, and heating has not been commanded. EcoVox will keep an eye on this zone to confirm that it is performing correctly going forward. The VAV 5_05 zone temp sensor has been frequently recording 0 degrees. EcoVox emailed UC Davis regarding some power trends that do not appear correct, but for now will continue to monitor both the data trends and the estimated power consumption based on equipment run characteristics. FCUs 01, 07, and 08 used to run 24/7 like other FCUs, but since February they have been cycling off more frequently. These three FCUs also maintain very low zone temperatures. The other FCUs tend towards having zone temperatures above setpoint, and do not enable cooling when this occurs. FCU 3 is especially warm, often above 80 degrees despite the supply air temperature for this area averaging 60 degrees. Contact us at 805.540.2044 if we can be of assistance with any of the action items.

rows.help: Total electric power consumption by Ghausi has decreased by 13% compared to May 2015, while peak electric demand has decreased by 13kW. The fans and pumps monitored by EcoVox accounted for 27% of total building power consumption in May, up significantly compared to previous months. This is mostly driven by a rise in AHU 03 and 04 average fan speed. Overnight building baseload averages 112kW, down from 130 kW during May 2015. The VAV 5_05 zone temperature sensor dropped out of range May 1-4 and again on May 13, but has performed well since. Some units, such as FCU 04 and VAV 5_04, tend to have zone temperature trends above setpoint. FCU 03 is often extremely warm, averaging 86-90 degrees. AHU 3 supply air temperature generally maintains setpoint or close to, but on May 18 rose far above. This caused associated zones to overheat as well. Some AHU 3 zones, such as VAV 3_06 and VAV 3_18 performed well during the first half of the month, but tended to be far above setpoint during the second half of the month. The supply airflow trends for AHUs 3-5 dropped offline May 25 through June 2, but have performed well since. EcoVox sent out the economizer report on May 23 and will work with the UC Davis team to ensure that outside air economizers are performing optimally. FCU 1 continues to run intermittently, and FCUs 7 and 8 rarely enabled throughout the month. AHU 5 has been exhibiting frequently overnight runtime outside of its normal schedule. Contact us at 805.540.2044 if we can be of assistance with any of the action items.

rows.help: Total electric power consumption during January was 280,000 kBTU, a 17% decrease compared to January 2016. Steam power consumption has increased by 9% to 609,000 kBTU. Chilled water power consumption trends have continued to remain static at 0 throughout the month, so EcoVox is unable to calculate year over year comparisons. Unoccupied baseline averages 105 kW, compared to 125 kW during January 2016. A number of control updates were implemented during January, including a new VAV heating valve strategy which greatly smoothed the oscillations which were previously seen in many zones, while still maintaining zone temperature setpoints well. Based on feedback from the UC Davis team, EcoVox is implementing updated sparks that have adjustable expected ranges for zone temperatures, separate from the occupant-adjustable zone setpoints. Time delays following change of occupancy will also be implemented. Later this month EcoVox will be importing additional occupancy and zone temperature setpoint trends. Contact us at 805.540.2044 if we can be of assistance with any of the action items.

rows.help: Total electric power consumption during September 2016 was 81,400 kWh, a 14% decrease compared to last year. Peak demand during the month was 215 kW, down from 222 kW last year. Total chilled water cooling consumption in Ghausi was 522,800 kBTU, 24% lower than during September 2015. Total steam heating consumption also decreased 20% compared to last year, to 202,600 kBTU during September 2016. Several VAV zones in Ghausi, including VAVs 1_02, 2_12, and 2_13, were noted to have heating valve. Sam determined that this was due to lack of a proper deadband, and is working with Mark to update the sequence. The zone temperature sensor for VAV 5_05 has been performing much better this month, and has been removed from the action items list below. AHU 5 has not been enabling overnight during recent days, most likely due to more temperate weather and zone temperatures staying within unoccupied setpoints. FCUs 2, 3, 4, and 6 continue to be quite warm, and do not enable cooling when they are above setpoint. AHUs 1 and 2 continue to maintain 1.5 inh2o supply air pressure, while AHUs 3-5 reset throughout the day. AHU 1 supply fan B tends to oscillate much more than fan B, despite the fact that they both maintain the same average temperature. There was a brief fault across the building on September 8 at 11:30 am, although there is no indication of what caused this. Many zones also experienced a heating failure on September 6-7 due to maintenance on the High Pressure Steam System. All units have performed correctly since. Contact us at 805.540.2044 if we can be of assistance with any of the action items.
